            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text continues the study of divisions by 2. Therefore, it is recommended to read the text *Two Sides* (<htcite0>) and its prerequisites before proceeding.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "112e532d-e8af-40d6-b1b5-527978ee42f3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Two Sides",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nOnce again, let’s start by looking at ourselves. Figure 1 shows a person’s two hands, representing the two sides of the body:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Left hand</td><td>Right hand</td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"imgLH\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgLH', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/Left_Hand.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img id=\"imgRH\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgRH', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/Right_Hand.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\">Figure 1: Hands reprsentation. © History Tracers. <span id=\"htImgCopyright\"></span></td></tr></table></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The figure shows a person's two hands raised with all fingers extended, each pointing toward a fruit.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Now, place your hands on a table or in front of you and answer Reflection 1:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Illusions...</b><br /><br />When we think about the sides of the body, is there something beyond those two sides?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_dimensions",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Stepping Out of the Plane\n\nFigure 1 had already been used in *History Tracers* in two situations where our goal was to show that the human body has two equal sides (<htcite0>; <htcite1>). However, the fact that those texts focused on this theme does not mean we were limited only to it.\n\n#### Going Deeper\n\nNow, place your hands the same way as in Graphic 1:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b5efc8f9-c268-430f-9681-7a43848ee48e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Editors",
                     "page": "Our Sides Are Equal",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "112e532d-e8af-40d6-b1b5-527978ee42f3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Two Sides",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><i class=\"fa-solid fa-hands-holding\" style=\"font-size:20em;color:#000;\"></i></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Graphic 1: Hands positioned as if to grab something. Images available in the free version of Font Awesome (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ad0cdae3-2260-4462-86a7-0987c6ffc82b'); return false;\">Font Awesome</a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Although we still see two hands in this graphic, from this new viewing angle we can observe that the two sides —which we can consider as dimensions— reveal yet another, which we call depth. This “new” dimension has always been present, but it was ignored for purely didactic reasons. This fact leads us to a reflection:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Depth</b><br /><br />Imagine you only had two dimensions, without the dimension of depth.<br /><br />Would it be possible to do everything you do in your life?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Plane\n\nWhen we mention that something has “only” two dimensions, such as flat surfaces (<htcite0>), we are usually simplifying reality. This simplification is clear because, when we look around us, we cannot find anything so thin that it can be reduced to just two dimensions. Even the sheets of paper we draw on have depth —small, but real.\n\n#### Mass\n\nThis impossibility of remaining restricted to two dimensions leads us to explore further our knowledge about the expansion of the universe. We return to Figure 2, which shows this expansion according to our current understanding (<htcite1>; <htcite2>; <htcite3>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0cb685b3-30b9-4c4b-8b8a-cb777c51208a",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Plane",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "6dfe4b3b-8338-46ab-8149-2e073414907e",
                     "text": "NASA",
                     "page": "Cosmic History",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a1a7c478-9061-4160-ba43-301c081733e9",
                     "text": "ESA",
                     "page": "History of Structure Formation",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "015c0ffc-d894-404a-b795-eebc8aec2744",
                     "text": "Lincoln, Don",
                     "page": "Cosmic Inflation",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2015",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/ESA/Planck_history_of_Universe.jpg\" id=\"imgESA2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgESA2', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 2: Planck, The History of the Universe. ©ESA – C. Carreau (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a1a7c478-9061-4160-ba43-301c081733e9'); return false;\"><i>ESA</i></a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "When the first particles and light emerged from the transformation of energy into matter, the particles acquired what we know as mass. As a consequence, this additional dimension we call depth came into being. Light, on the other hand, does not have mass.\n\nThe reason particles have mass was proposed by Higgs in <htdate0> and confirmed at CERN laboratories in <htdate1>. According to Higgs, the fact that particles have mass is due to an interaction with something invisible to our eyes: the field. Light, by not interacting with this field, has no mass (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ae8d4e6a-8916-4d56-97a5-af126bc7e620",
                     "text": "CERN",
                     "page": "The Higgs Boson",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1964",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2012",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: The Universe and Us</b><br /><br />We possess the same energy that was present in the universe at its beginning. We have mass and therefore more than one dimension, thanks to the way the universe evolved. In this way, we are part of the universe, just like everything around us.<br /><br />If everything we see has at least three dimensions, why should we limit our explanations to only two?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "Tudo no universo é plano?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "No",
         "additionalInfo": "Quando falamos em plano, estamos excluindo profundidade que assuntos e a natureza possuí, limitando nosso conhecimento e explicações sobre algo. Apesar de ser tentador nos limitarmos a isto, devemos tentar ir além, evitando reduzir ainda mais ao eu."
